  "stage": {
    "id": "decentralization_token_economy",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Module 2: Decentralization & Token Economy",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "decentralization_consensus",
        "title": "Decentralization & Consensus Mechanisms",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Three axes of decentralization: architectural, political, logical (Vitalik Buterin)\n- Three justifications: fault tolerance, attack resistance, collusion resistance\n- Common mode failure: same software/team/country undermines decentralization\n- Byzantine fault tolerance and Nakamoto consensus\n- DID (Decentralized Identifier) and headless brands\n\n**Vitalik Buterin** analyzes decentralization along three independent axes.\n\nLet's use a **building** as an analogy. **Architectural decentralization** is like a building supported by multiple pillars — if one collapses, the building still stands. **Political decentralization** means no one on the building's management committee can become a dictator. **Logical decentralization** asks whether there is one blueprint or many.\n\nBlockchain occupies a curious position: it is politically and architecturally decentralized, yet logically centralized — because the entire network behaves as a single shared state.\n\nThe three justifications for decentralization are: (1) **fault tolerance** — eliminating single points of failure, (2) **attack resistance** — the cost of an attack scales with the size of the system, (3) **collusion resistance** — it is difficult for dispersed participants to conspire. However, beware of **common mode failures** (same software, same dev team, same country) — true decentralization stems from diversity.\n\n**DID (Decentralized Identifier)** and the **headless brand** concept are also important. Bitcoin is a prime example of a headless brand — even after Satoshi disappeared, the community continued to evolve the brand.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "strong_weak_technology",
        "title": "Strong & Weak Technology / Metaverse",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Strong tech reshapes the world to itself; weak tech adapts to the current world (Chris Dixon)\n- Historical pattern: strong tech wins — Wikipedia over Encarta, iPhone over BlackBerry, Tesla over hybrids\n- Hype cycle: blockchain must pass the Trough of Disillusionment\n- Seven metaverse essentials: decentralization, property rights, identity, composability, open source, community ownership, reputation\n- Web3 GTM: community-first, not product-first\n\n**Chris Dixon's** strong vs. weak technology framework is a powerful lens for predicting the future of technology.\n\nPut simply, **weak technology** is like putting a faster horse-drawn carriage on existing roads, while **strong technology** is building an entirely new highway. Weak technology looks more realistic early on, but history repeatedly proves that strong technology defines new eras.\n\nKey examples: Wikipedia vs. Encarta, iPhone (touch + apps) vs. BlackBerry (physical keyboard), Tesla (fully electric) vs. hybrids. Public blockchain + cryptocurrency is a **strong technology**, while private blockchain is a weak technology.\n\nThe seven metaverse essentials are also critical: decentralization, property rights, self-sovereign identity, composability, open source, community-owned economy, and identity with reputation. All of these must be in place for a true metaverse to emerge.\n\nWeb3's GTM (Go-To-Market) strategy is equally interesting. While Web2 follows 'product first, community later,' Web3 puts **purpose and community first**. Compound's liquidity mining is a textbook case — TVL exploded from $100M to $600M.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "tokenology",
        "title": "Tokenology: The Science of Token Design",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Tokens enable open network design — solving the funding problem of open protocols\n- ERC-20 (fungible): transfer(), approve(), balanceOf() / ERC-721 (NFT): ownerOf(), tokenURI()\n- Tokenology vs tokenomics: vector (direction+meaning) vs scalar (size only)\n- Four design spaces: ownership, alignment, incentive, access\n- Equation of exchange M×V=P×Q — high velocity = low price; solution: staking, governance, fee sharing\n\n**Common Computer (2024)** Chapter 6 views tokens not merely as currency, but as **tools for network design**.\n\nLet's compare tokens to **parking tokens**. Traditional tokenomics only asks \"How many tokens exist and what are they worth?\" (scalar). **Tokenology**, on the other hand, analyzes \"What behavior does this token incentivize, who should hold it, and where does value originate?\" (vector).\n\nTokenology's four design spaces are: (1) **ownership** — user-owned and operated services, (2) **alignment** — direct connection between creators and fans, (3) **incentive** — coordinating validators and miners, (4) **access** — tiered service experiences.\n\nThe most practical concept is the **equation of exchange** M×V=P×Q. When token velocity (V) is high — meaning people sell immediately after receiving — the price stays low. The solution is to design holding incentives: staking, governance rights, and fee sharing to reduce velocity.\n\n**Metcalfe's Law** (network value = N²) is also important. Just as Facebook's revenue scales with MAU², Bitcoin and Ethereum prices also show high correlation with Metcalfe's Law.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "In the equation of exchange M×V=P×Q, what is an effective strategy to increase token price?",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "Increase token velocity (V) — circulate faster",
        "Decrease token velocity (V) — design holding incentives like staking and governance",
        "Reduce service transaction volume (Q)",
        "Increase total token supply (M)"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Decrease token velocity (V) — design holding incentives like staking and governance",
